Research keywords: Conduct keyword research to identify the relevant keywords for your website. Use tools such as Google Keyword Planner, SEMrush, or Ahrefs to find out what keywords people are searching for related to your niche.

Optimize meta tags: Include the relevant keywords in your meta tags, including the title tag, meta description, and header tags (H1, H2, H3).

Optimize content: Use the keywords naturally throughout your website's content. Ensure that the content is high-quality, informative, and relevant to the user's search intent.

Use descriptive URLs: Use descriptive URLs that include the relevant keywords, rather than generic URLs that don't give any indication of what the page is about.

Optimize images: Optimize images by using descriptive alt tags, compressing their size, and using relevant file names.

Improve website speed: Google considers website speed as an important ranking factor, so it's essential to optimize your website's speed. Use tools like Google PageSpeed Insights or GTmetrix to identify areas of improvement.

Use internal linking: Link to other relevant pages on your website to improve the user's experience and help search engines understand the structure of your website.

Make it mobile-friendly: Ensure that your website is optimized for mobile devices. Use a responsive design and test it on various devices to ensure that it's easy to use on all screen sizes.

Use schema markup: Use schema markup to help search engines understand the content on your website better.

Track your progress: Use tools like Google Analytics or Search Console to track your website's progress and identify areas for improvement.
